	<p pid="a.111.2/1">As at <phrase class="date" code="2006-01-01">1 January 2006</phrase>, the number of self-declared adherents of the faiths listed currently serving in the Armed Forces were as follows.</p>
	<table>
		<tbody>
			<tr pid="a.111.2/4"> <td>Muslim</td> <td>Hindu</td> <td>Sikh</td> <td>Buddhist</td> </tr>
			<tr pid="a.111.2/5"> <td>320</td> <td>250</td> <td>85</td> <td>245</td> </tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>
	<p pid="a.111.2/8">Source: DASA (Tri-Service)</p>
	<p pid="a.111.2/9">1. UK Regular forces includes nursing services and excludes full-time Reserve service personnel, Gurkhas, the Home Service battalions of the Royal Irish Regiment, mobilised reservists and naval activated reservists.</p>
	<p pid="a.111.2/10">2. Figures include both trained and untrained personnel.</p>
	<p pid="a.111.2/11">3. Figures have been rounded to the nearest five to prevent disclosure of sensitive personal data.</p>
	<p pid="a.111.2/12">4. Due to rounding methods used, totals may not always equal the sum of the parts.</p>
	<p pid="a.111.2/13">The conditioned working hours for the respective chaplains to the Armed Forces are as follows.</p>
	<table>
		<tbody>
			<tr pid="a.111.2/16"> <td>Muslim</td> <td>Hindu</td> <td>Sikh</td> <td>Buddhist</td> </tr>
			<tr pid="a.111.2/17"> <td>36 hours per week (a full-time appointment)</td> <td>22 &frac12; hours per week</td> <td>15 hours per week</td> <td>15 hours per week</td> </tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>
	<p pid="a.111.2/20">The working hours for these posts are currently under review.</p>
</reply>
